{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17654764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17654764"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:54:54+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:54:54+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18630"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18630","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18630"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11362"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113219"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11362","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11362"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18630"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95246"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10284"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26368"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26371"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113219","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113219"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003ESmooth muscle tissue contains fascicles arranged in different orientations. Circular fascicles are particularly important in hollow organs of the body.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary independent function of circular muscle fascicles?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increases organ length when contracted","Stabilises organ position","Maintains constant organ volume","Decreases organ diameter when contracted","Propels contents in one direction"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe primary function of circular muscle fascicles is that they \u003Cstrong\u003Edecrease organ diameter when contracted\u003C/strong\u003E. These muscle fibres are arranged in concentric rings around hollow organs such as the intestines and blood vessels. When circular muscles contract, they reduce the diameter of the organ or lumen. This action is crucial for functions like controlling the flow of substances (e.g., food, blood, urine) through the organ. They work in coordination with longitudinal muscles to facilitate processes such as peristalsis and sphincter control.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreases organ length when contracted\u003C/strong\u003E - This is the function of longitudinal muscle fibres, not circular fascicles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintains constant organ volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Organ volume changes with muscle contraction and relaxation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPropels contents in one direction\u003C/strong\u003E - This requires coordinated contraction of both circular and longitudinal muscles\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilises organ position\u003C/strong\u003E - This is primarily achieved through connective tissue attachments, not muscle arrangement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Circular fascicles in smooth muscle wrap around hollow organs in concentric rings to control luminal diameter.","Contraction of circular muscle fascicles decreases the diameter of hollow organs.","Circular muscle arrangement is essential for peristalsis and sphincter function in the gastrointestinal tract."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95246"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18630"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95246","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/95246"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-10T13:51:26+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-10T13:51:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11362"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113219"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:5